[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering resource loading**\n\nI’m recalling that resource bundles need to be included explicitly, with both properties and class. It might generate proxy code, and I wonder if a custom ClassLoader could return a properties resource URL to use in-memory bytes, avoiding the need for a class bundle. However, I think native images can’t include runtime-generated resources. If the ClassLoader streams bytes, it may still try using a class bundle first. There could be issues with dynamic class loading in native images, especially regarding which classes are included.\n\n**Exploring resource bundle access**\n\nI’m thinking about how line target resources getBundle could be affected. Dynamic access may involve metadata records for the resource bundle basename. I wonder if a custom classloader impacts this if it’s not on the classpath. The agent might still record information. I’m considering if ResourceBundle.getBundle will work with a native run after the agent’s metadata. It seems that custom class loaders might still supply resources at runtime, but I need to confirm if native images optimize resource bundle lookups.\n\n**Clarifying Java test conventions**\n\nI'm looking at guidance that says to keep test coverage for each dynamic-access class in its own Java test file, which makes sense. But then it mentions not using `$` in test class or file names. We have a nested class in our test file called ViewDefinitions, and its bytecode includes `$`. Is this forbidden? I’m wondering if the restriction applies only to top-level classes. I also think we should avoid using reflection directly, and it might be useful to inspect the git diff.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0ee6aa249f844b8c016a10f7258ba081a18c187b424da0f04a\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqEPc8gO4dOxyqHGhZNJLfrH1IyT0-00zdX2jZIBKXLZTVwsUpxefD-48c-EVoM7drMgko8oBjhOluOsH2CFY-sili