cially regarding which classes are included.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring resource bundle access**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how line target resources getBundle could be affected. Dynamic access may involve metadata records for the resource bundle basename. I wonder if a custom classloader impacts this if it’s not on the classpath. The agent might still record information. I’m considering if ResourceBundle.getBundle will work with a native run after the agent’s metadata. It seems that custom class loaders might still supply resources at runtime, but I need to confirm if native images optimize resource bundle lookups.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying Java test conventions**\\n\\nI'm looking at guidance that says to keep test coverage for each dynamic-access class in its own Java test file, which makes sense. But then it mentions not using `$` in test class or file names. We have a nested class in our test file called ViewDefinitions, and its bytecode includes `$`. Is this forbidden? I’m wondering if the restriction applies only to top-level classes. I also think we should avoid using reflection directly, and it might be useful to inspect the git diff.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_XciQZtIsUy1y4NRIQtmFn1kx|fc_0ee6aa249f844b8c016a10f73c21d481a18395ad994bd20bb3", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "git diff -- tests/src/org.springframework/spring-webmvc/5.3.18/src/test/java/org_springframework/spring_webmvc/ResourceBundleViewResolverTest.java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 842, "output": 1453, "cacheRead": 24064, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 26359, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779496740320, "responseId": "resp_0ee6aa249f844b8c016a10f724d16481a192266870817f6113"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_XciQZtIsUy1y4NRIQtmFn1kx|fc_0ee6aa249f84